   "source": [
    "## 24. Final Conclusion\n",
    "\n",
    "This project applied supervised machine learning to classify emails as spam or ham using the UCI Spambase dataset. The dataset represents emails through 57 engineered features, including word frequencies, character frequencies, and capital-letter run lengths.\n",
    "\n",
    "Five classifiers were compared:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Logistic Regression\n",
    "- Gaussian Naive Bayes\n",
    "- K-Nearest Neighbors\n",
    "- Decision Tree\n",
    "- Random Forest\n",
    "\n",
    "The models were evaluated using stratified five-fold cross-validation and an independent test set. Accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, and ROC-AUC were reported because no single metric fully describes spam-filter performance.\n",
    "\n",
    "The model selected by the notebook is the classifier with the highest test F1-score. Its confusion matrix and classification report show how well it detects spam while avoiding the incorrect classification of legitimate emails. The feature analysis also demonstrates that both email vocabulary and formatting patterns contribute to spam detection.\n",
    "\n",
    "Overall, the results show that supervised machine learning can classify emails effectively when trained on labeled examples. A practical production system should continue to monitor false positives, update the model as spam language changes, and evaluate performance on emails from a broader range of users.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
